  "extraTiles": [],
  "textBoxes": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "x": 180,
      "y": -150,
      "w": 680,
      "h": 44,
      "text": "Title: Logic Families",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "x": 180,
      "y": -100,
      "w": 680.4420952102233,
      "h": 67.11127891355548,
      "text": "Description: Demonstration of the differences between 74 chip families.",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "x": -403.7599591303084,
      "y": 141.24216008668296,
      "w": 780,
      "h": 150,
      "text": "(RED) (1A, pin 1) = a button to +5V with NO pull-down -- the classic beginner mistake. Pressed = HIGH; released = FLOATING. On 74LS the floating TTL input self-biases HIGH through its internal ~100k pull-up, so the LED stays ON even after you release. Switch to 74HC and the same released input reads LOW. Same wires, opposite result -- on real silicon a floating CMOS input can sit anywhere and drift. GREEN (2A) = the same button plus a 10k pull-down: a clean LOW in every family. YELLOW (3A) = a 10k pull-up with a button to GND (active-low): idle HIGH in every family. Rule: every input needs a defined level -- a driver, a pull-up, or a pull-down.",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "x": 180,
      "y": 444.8894761974441,
      "w": 781.7778197283889,
      "h": 125.77744217288905,
      "text": "(BLUE). The 12k/10k divider feeds a fixed ~2.3 V into buffer 4A (pin 9). Is 2.3 V a HIGH or a LOW? Depends who you ask: 74LS switches near 1.4 V, so it says HIGH and the blue LED lights. 74HC is pure CMOS and switches near 2.5 V (VIH 3.5 V!), so it says LOW -- blue goes dark. 74HCT is CMOS inside but built with TTL thresholds exactly so it can read signals like this one: flip to HCT and blue comes back. 74LVC keeps TTL-style thresholds too. ",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "x": 180,
      "y": 580,
      "w": 780,
      "h": 140,
      "text": "(WHITE). Buffer 5 (5A tied HIGH) drives six LED branches from one output pin. Every output has internal resistance: about 714 ohms for 74LS, 150 for 74HC/HCT, 50 for 74LVC. On 74LS the six loads drag the output down to ~2.3 V, below the LED forward voltage plus margin, so the whole bank sits dark: the output is overloaded. Switch to 74HC and the stiffer driver holds ~3.1 V: all six light dimly. On 74LVC (~3.9 V) they are clearly brighter. Fan-out is this same idea with gate inputs as the load: one 74LS output is rated to drive 10 LS inputs, while CMOS families are rated for ~50 CMOS inputs (their inputs draw almost no DC current). More loads than the rating and your HIGH stops being a HIGH.",
      "v": 2
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "x": 180,
      "y": 740,
      "w": 780,
      "h": 140,
      "text": "Speed: max usable clock is roughly 35 MHz for 74LS, 25 MHz for 74HC/HCT, and 100 MHz for 74LVC, the low-voltage CMOS family (its bipolar cousin 74LVT is similar for this lesson). The stiffer the output driver (Station 3), the faster it charges wire and input capacitance -- drive and speed are the same physics. Power: 74LS draws milliamps constantly just being powered (bipolar bias currents), while CMOS families draw microamps standing still and only spend energy when switching (charge x voltage x frequency, CV^2f). That is why battery-powered logic is CMOS.",
      "v": 2
    }
  ],
